text: hey everyone nice thinny mean tano here
the internet's busiest music nerd and
it's time for a review of the new still
woozy album if this isn't nice i don't
know what is this is the debut record of
sven eric gamsky under the still woozy
name a songwriter singer and producer
who's been racking up millions of
streams with his own brand of self-made
alternative r b and bedroom pop prime
cuts like habit and goody bag may not
have the strongest vocals on the planet
but that's easily made up for with
snappy hooks and some home spun warmth
coming off the instrumentals those
tracks are a few years old at this point
but some of the new material teasing
toward this debut did catch my attention
kenny for example is a droney acoustic
psycpop ballad with intoxicating vocal
harmonies very sentimental lyrics it's
quite nice but beyond that i didn't
really know what else to expect from
this record as still woozy doesn't
marry himself strictly to one two or
three musical styles and while i found
if this isn't nice to be a versatile
record i also found it to be a
derivative one too as the more i
listened the less i actually got the
appeal of this lp for the most part the
music is okay but it doesn't execute
anything with a substantial amount of
finesse or flair and for something
presenting with a bedroom pop aesthetic
the sound of it is pretty safe and clean
i mean yeah the rhythm section is mostly
beats which are pretty punchy and there
is something warm about the way the bass
keys and vocals compress together but
outside of that nothing about this
record is all that organic or textured
or original for example the opening
track wolf whose neurotic lyrics i like
a lot but the music sounds like a
collaboration between foster the people
and uh unknown mortal orchestra at
gunpoint meanwhile the track rocky is
just a poor attempt at forcing of
montreal vocals over a team impala
record the kevin barnes-esque vocal
arrangements continue on to the song
that's life where i actually have a hard
time taking some of the writing
seriously she's my guiding star she's on
my tarot card this feels like i'm
listening to an ajr song but with a much
smaller budget behind it and how's the
track what the [ __ ] not a bedroom pop
take on a 21 pilot song that you would
listen to in the car with the windows
rolled up in addition to all of this i
found the singing on this lp to be
painfully average too it's easy to
ignore that for a song or two especially
since gamsky harmonizes well and has a
knack for song structure but for one
song after another the vocals just
become so monotonous before you or me is
yet another moment on the lp that sounds
like a rip-off of of montreal suntlantic
twins but take out the personality the
colorful instrumentation the queer
pizzazz but the track window does
deliver a refreshing change of pace in
the track list with a punchier beat some
more overt nods to the sounds of r b
that put still woozi's biggest tracks on
the map to begin with there are some
knowingly corny spots in the lyrics but
damn the groove
and the eclectic instrumentation as well
as some of those uh soulful vocal chops
worked into the beat are too good to
ignore plus also is that a sample of a
chair squeaking in the instrumental you
know it's this kind of fun creative
attitude and color that i think a great
deal of this record lacks the vocals on
the track all along actually do deliver
some bite though along with some guitars
that have a bit of a southern flavor
these tracks along with kenny do come
together into a handful of highlights
but for the most part i found this
record to be just very uninspired bland
it was like i was disappointed by a rex
orange county album without actually
listening to rex orange county granted
still woozy is pulling from a lot of
different interesting places
stylistically pop psych r b hip hop rock
etc but i feel like i'm merely hearing
an even safer take on an already very
safe array of alt-centric sounds that
come together in a way that's far from
terrible but also far from memorable too
feeling a strong four to a light five on
this one tran position have you given
this record a listen did you love it did
you hate it what would you rate it
